heron</i>. Compare   Hearn   and   Heron  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from (Le) Héron in France (Seine-Maritime)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":6,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Heron was born about 1218, in Northumberland, England, his father, Jordan de Héron IV, was 20 and his mother, Isabel de Néville, was 27. He married Emeline de Héron in 1237, in Hadston, Northumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1257, in Ford, Northumberland, England, at the age of 40."},"et":{"Abt 1218–1257":"umbes 1218–1257","1216–Female":"1216–Surnud","1218–1257":"1218–1257","1225–1300":"1225–1300","–1256":"–1256","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1193–Female":"1193–Surnud","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1193":"1193","Abt 1218":"umbes 1218","after 1247":"pärast 1247","1216":"1216","1237":"1237","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1257":"1257","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1300":"1300","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1200":"1200","about 1240":"umbes 1240","1218":"1